1. f4 {Rapid Teams tournament at EsPion. I'm playing on Board 3. Edward and I
have played before but neither of us can remember where. It wasn't classical,
cos his name is new to me. It means Truth-Sayer.} 1... Nf6 {I've arrived a
little late for the game before the clock started. I take my time to set up and
pull out my notebook. I'm the only one in the room writing down my pieces. I
feel it helps slow me down, which is especially important for me in the
middlegame. I generally don't stop writing till the 3/4min mark.} 2. Nf3 e6 3.
e3 d5 4. d4 Nbd7 {Overly cautious.} 5. Bd3 c5 6. c3 cxd4 7. exd4 Bd6 8. O-O Qc7
9. Ne5 g6 {I never like seeing this. Means no Greek Gift.} 10. Nd2 O-O 11. Qf3
Bxe5 {I was away from the board when this was played, meaning he took some time
to play it. Seems wild to me.} 12. fxe5 Nh5 13. Qh3 (13. g4 {Also considered.})
13... Qd8 14. g4 Ng7 15. Nf3 f6 16. Bd2 b6 {A very waity move.} 17. Rf2 {Also a
very waity move, and not necessary.} 17... a5 18. Bh6 (18. Raf1 {I realize now
that Rf2 should always be followed by Raf1, cos without it the rooks remain
disconnected. This sounds obvious but I felt like I've learnt it afresh today.})
18... Rf7 19. Raf1 Ba6 {Wrong side of the board.} 20. Bxa6 Rxa6 21. Bxg7 Rxg7
22. exf6 Nxf6 23. g5 {Some poor judgement here. This gifts the e4 outpost to the
knight.} (23. Ne5 {Now Ne4 would lose a queen (for 2 rooks).} 23... Ne4 24. Rf8+
Qxf8 25. Rxf8+ Kxf8) 23... Nh5 24. Qxe6+ Kh8 25. Ne5 Qxg5+ 26. Kh1 h6 {At this
point an arbiter steps in to point out that our clock hasn't been adding
increment. As he works to correct the clock, I have plenty of time to calculate
ahead (I have lots of time anyway) and I eventually find a practical mate in 5
that I'm super proud of.} 27. Nf7+ Rxf7 28. Qe8+ {My opponent resigns here but
I'll show you the full mate.} 28... Kh7 29. Rxf7+ Ng7 30. Rxg7+ Kxg7 31. Rf7#
{[%c_effect
h1;square;h1;type;Winner;animated;true,g7;square;g7;type;CheckmateBlack;animated;true]}
1-0

