{Disclaimer: White is 2.5 years old at the time of this game.} 1. f3! 
{[%c_effect f3;square;f3;type;GreatFind;persistent;true]} 1... d5 {White's first
instinct was to play pawn to e5, and he was disappointed to hear that this was
not a legal move. Instead he played 1. f3, the Barnes Opening.} 2. e3 Nc6 {White
is enjoying pawn moves.} 3. d4 Nf6 {White moves a pawn two squares ! From this
point we are doing a congratulatory handshake after every move.} 4. Bd3
{Excellent piece development from White.} 4... g6 5. Nh3? {[%c_effect
h3;square;h3;type;Mistake;keyPressed;undefined;persistent;true] White has been
informed that the knight can only move to e2 or h3, and he picks the worse
option.} 5... Bxh3 {Black captures the first piece of the game ! White is
shooketh !} 6. gxh3 Bg7 {White's instinct was to do any number of other
recaptures, but is assured that this is the only legal one.} 7. Kd2?!
{[%c_effect d2;square;d2;type;Inaccuracy;keyPressed;undefined;persistent;true]}
7... e5 {A strange move, possibly made because the king is the tallest piece.}
8. Rf1?! {[%c_effect
f1;square;f1;type;Inaccuracy;keyPressed;undefined;persistent;true] White wants
to capture the pawns on f3 and h3 with his rook, but is disappointed to hear
that not only are those illegal moves, those are also his own pawns.} 8... exd4
{[%c_effect e8;square;e8;type;Winner;animated;true] Here White insists moves his
king to c3. He is informed that the move is illegal, but he insists on moving it
there anyway. After 3 attempts to get him to move something else, he loses
patience and knocks over all the pieces, which I think is tantamount to a
resignation.} 0-1

