1. e4 {SGA game against Amsterdam West. My opponent is a young kid, very silent
and avoiding all eye contact. We are similarly rated, although I didn't know
that at the time.} 1... d6 2. d4 g6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. Bc4 c6 {My plan
here is usually to play b5-b4 and win the pawn with Nxe4.} 6. d5 {This feels
like a mistake.} 6... b5 7. Bb3 b4 8. Ne2 (8. e5 {This is usually the move, but
it doesn't work here since White has already moved the d4 pawn.}) 8... Nxe4 9.
dxc6 O-O?? {[%c_effect
g8;square;g8;type;Blunder;size;100%25;animated;false;persistent;true] Horrible
blunder. White is now losing a piece.} (9... Nxc6 {I had already seen that this
doesn't work, cos White can threaten mate while attacking two knights.} 10. Qd5!
{[%c_effect
d5;square;d5;type;GreatFind;size;100%25;animated;false;persistent;true]}) (9...
e6 {This had to be played to stop the bishop from coming in.}) (9... Nf6 {Also
works. Anything to guard d5 really.} 10. Bd5 Nxd5 11. Qxd5 O-O 12. c7 {Same
trick doesn't work with the queen, as it can be trapped.} 12... Qxc7 13. Qxa8
Nc6) (9... Qb6?? {[%c_effect
b6;square;b6;type;Blunder;size;100%25;animated;false;persistent;true]} 10. Qd5!
{[%c_effect
d5;square;d5;type;GreatFind;size;100%25;animated;false;persistent;true]} 10...
Qxf2+) 10. Bd5 {Missed this completely.} 10... Nxf2 {Desperado move, to get a
measly pawn and expose the White king a bit.} 11. Kxf2 Qb6+ {Unnecessary,
prompts white bishop to develop with tempo. Could've gone straight to c7.} 12.
Be3 Qc7 13. c3 bxc3 14. Nxc3 a6 (14... Nxc6 {Didn't play this because I was
worried about the knight invading with Nb5.} 15. Nb5 Qd7) 15. Qb3 Nxc6 16. Bxc6
Qxc6 17. Rac1 Be6 {Gets a tempo, but this impedes my pawns for a while.} 18. Qd1
Rab8 19. Qd2 Qd7 20. Bd4 f6 {Just trying to avoid trades.} 21. Rhe1 Bc4 {Another
unnecessary move that immediately loses a tempo.} 22. b3 Bf7 23. Ne4 Bd5 (23...
Rfc8) 24. Bb2 (24. Bxf6 {White can sac for a pawn.} 24... Bxf6) 24... Bc6 25.
Qe2 Bb5 {Mentally I'm not in a great space at this point. Only 2 boards are
still playing and we have practically already lost the match. I'm just playing
on right now to use up some clock, maybe put some time pressure, but it never
comes to that.} 26. Qe3 Bc6 27. Rcd1 Qb7 (27... Rfc8 {Was begging to be played
at many points during the game. Open file, why not.}) 28. Qd3 f5 29. Nc3 Qb6+
30. Kf1 {This is a good sign. I can now remove the white c3 knight and win an
exchange to come back to material equallty.} 30... Bxc3 31. Qxc3 {White is one
more away from checkmate.} 31... Bb5+ {Dwight, who is spectating, misses that
this move is check and thinks I just blundered a mate-in-one, and walks out of
the room in disgust.} 32. Re2 Bxe2+ {This is tempting, but actually Black can
maintain the tension for a while since the white king isn't going anywhere.}
(32... e5 {Would've been so much safer.}) 33. Kxe2 Rf6 {An absolutely trash move
that immediately loses the material equality I had fought so hard for.} (33...
e5 {A natural looking move, but it is also a mistake.} 34. Qc4+ Kh8) (33... Qb5+
{Black is a point up in material, and should trade queens.} 34. Kf2 (34. Ke1 Qb4
35. Qxb4 Rxb4) 34... Qc5+ 35. Qxc5 dxc5) 34. Qc4+ Rf7 35. Ng5 {White will once
again go up a piece.} 35... Rf8 {Interestingly this is a mistake. Engine says
Black should trade queens here and that would be better.} (35... Qb5 36. Qxb5
axb5 37. Nxf7 Kxf7 {Honestly I don't see how this is that much better.}) 36.
Nxf7 Rxf7 37. Rc1 Qb7 {This move kind of shows how tired I am. I'm playing for
tricks, hoping he won't see the threat on the g2 pawn, but instead he can now
safely trade queens.} 38. Qc8+ Qxc8 39. Rxc8+ Rf8 40. Rxf8+ {Interesting choice,
I would've thought that White would want to hold on the rooks since I have so
many extra pawns.} 40... Kxf8 41. Ke3 e5 42. a4 Ke7 43. b4 Kd7 44. b5 axb5 45.
axb5 Kc7 46. Ba3 Kb6 47. Bxd6 Kxb5 {Touch move!} (47... e4 {I had calculated
that I would need to play this first to hold on to the extra pawn and capture
the b5 pawn later, but when the moment came I touched the king too quickly and
then had to move it.}) 48. Bxe5 Kc5 49. Kf4 Kd5 50. h4 Ke6 51. Bc3 Kf7 52. g4
fxg4 53. Kxg4 h6 54. Bd2 Kg7 55. Kf3 {I don't quite understand this move, but I
guess he's making his own quiet calculations of distant opposition.} 55... Kh7
56. Ke4 Kg7 57. Ke5 h5 {More hope chess. I'm thinking I'll play g5 at some point
and he'll capture with the pawn, causing the pawn to change promotion square
colour.} (57... g5 58. h5 Kf7) 58. Bg5 {Ends the game really.} 58... Kf7 59. Kd6
Kg7 60. Ke6 Kg8 61. Kf6 {[%c_effect
f6;square;f6;type;Winner;animated;true,g8;square;g8;type;ResignBlack;animated;true]
Resignation.} 1-0

