[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[WhiteElo "1502"]
[BlackElo "1738"]
[TimeControl "5400+30"]

1. f4 {Martin is rated 200+ points higher than me. I come into this game
thinking I'd be happy with a draw, since that would secure 2.5 points which is
my goal for 5 games, and this is only my fourth.} 1... c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Bf5 4.
d4 e6 5. Bd3 Bxd3 {Obviously not what I want, I like my light bishop. But theek
hai.} 6. Qxd3 (6. cxd3 {Robert Ramirex and my engine both prefer this, but this
looks insane to me.}) 6... Bd6 7. Nbd2 Ne7 8. O-O Nf5 {A strange knight.} 9. b3
Nd7 10. Bb2 O-O 11. Rac1 Re8 12. Ne5 f6 13. Ng4 h5 {Overreaching IMO.} 14. Nf2
Nh6 15. Qg6 {A nice square for the queen. Do I have an attack?} 15... h4 {Most
intuitive way to defend the pawn.} (15... Nf5 {A creative way to do it.} 16.
Qxh5 Nxe3) 16. Ng4 {I'm not thrilled about this move that allows Black to lose
the bad knight, but I can't think of another way to get my rook in the game.}
16... Nxg4 17. Qxg4 f5 18. Qh5 Be7 {This basically denies the g5 square for any
incoming knights.} 19. Nf3 {Still not a rook.} 19... Nf8 {A knight on f8 means
never mate. Maybe my rook won't be useful either.} 20. Ne5 {Saw this pretty last
second. I can now see that I have a perpetual check if I want it.} 20... Bf6
{And this allows it.} 21. Qf7+ {A few checks to feel him out and see if he's
going to blunder a queen.} 21... Kh8 22. Qh5+ {My thinking is that a draw
against a higher rated opponent gets me points anyway, and I get to play the
last round of the day with zero pressure since the tournament is already a
success. I clearly has some initiative here but I guess I'm too chicken to play
on with a single pawn advantage.} (22. Qxb7 Bxe5 23. fxe5 Qg5) (22. Ba3 {This is
the real continuation of the attack, but I never really consider it.} 22... b6
(22... Be7 23. Qh5+ Kg8) 23. Bxf8 Rxf8 24. Ng6+ Kh7 25. Nxf8+ Qxf8 26. Qxe6)
22... Kg8 (22... Nh7 {Wouldn't this be great?} 23. Nf7+) 23. Qf7+ {I offer a
draw, which my opponent has to accept cos I'm clearly about to force it. He
gives me an expression of mingled disgust and disappointment. Fair enough.}
1/2-1/2

[Event "Daniel Noteboomtoernooi"]
[Site "Leiden"]
[Date "2026.02.21"]
[Round "4"]
[White "Guus van Putten"]
[Black "Harman Singh"]
[Result "0-1"]
[WhiteElo "0"]
[BlackElo "1502"]
[TimeControl "5400+30"]

1. d4 {Guus is unrated but he beat someone rated 1662 in the first round. We
start the round with some small talk. He told me he had a win, a bye and a loss.
I said I had a bye, a loss and two wins. He asked how I could have two wins. I
said I was counting this one. We both laughed. He said \\\"Well you better win
this now.\\\" I did.} 1... g6 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Nf3 d6 5. Bg5 Nbd7 6. e3
a6 7. a4 c6 8. Bd3 {Every time someone puts a bishop on d3 I start seeing dreams
of an e4 pawn fork.} 8... O-O 9. O-O Re8 {Setting up the fork, but there's a
long way to go.} 10. h3 h6 11. Bh4 {This is useful, means I can play g5 and get
the fork if all goes well.} 11... e5 12. Qc2 {This generally means the fork
isn't happening, unless I can get a bishop on b7 as well. But that c6 pawn is a
hindrance, so I need to handle this with my queen.} 12... Qe7 13. dxe5 dxe5 {Is
it going to happen ?} 14. Rad1 {Yes it is ! A central fork is now imminent}
14... g5 {Step one of the fork, but my worthy opponent sees it right away.
Rather than wait for the fork to come to him, he takes matters into his own
hands and sacs a knight.} 15. Nxg5 hxg5 16. Bxg5 {White has 2 pawns for a bishop
and Black's king is exposed. The engine likes it for Black, but I will now make
a series of positional mistakes that will cause me a lot of trouble} 16... Nc5
17. Bf5 e4 {Cuts off the bishop and forces a trade. I like trades, I'm up a
piece.} 18. Bxc8 Raxc8 19. Rd4 Qe6 20. b4 Nfd7 {Engine hates this, cos I'm
saccing two pieces for a rook, which tempers my advantage.} (20... Nh7 {So much
better. Attacks two pieces and wins me material.} 21. bxc5 Bxd4 22. exd4) 21.
bxc5 Bxd4 (21... Nxc5) 22. exd4 Qxc4 23. Qd2 Qe6 {Another positional misstep,
pieces going backwards.} (23... Qd3) 24. Re1 f5 25. Bh6 Qg6 {I really want to
trade queens.} 26. Qf4 Kf7 {Outright blunders a pawn.} 27. Rxe4 Rxe4 28. Nxe4
{Not a good trade, and this knight is going to be so annoying for me.} 28... Kg8
29. Nd6 Rb8 30. Nxf5 Qf7 {The bishop blocks the forking square. I offer a draw
here but Guus wisely refuses.} 31. g4 {I wonder what the thinking behind this
was.} (31. Qg5+ {Practically game ending. Black will lose a queen shortly.}
31... Kh7 32. Bg7 {Quiet move that sets up future checks.} 32... Qg6 {PLEASE
TRADE} 33. Qh4+ {No} 33... Kg8 34. Ne7+) 31... Re8 32. Qg5+ {Finally checks.}
32... Kh7 33. f3 Re6 34. Nd6 {Tempting to take the outpost and attack the queen,
but White should be going for the kill.} 34... Qg6 {Finally forces a queen
trade.} 35. Qxg6+ Kxg6 {Took with the king to hold on to the open file.} (35...
Rxg6) 36. Bf4 Rf6 {A harmless threat, White simply blocks with the knight right
?} 37. Bg3 {Huge blunder IMO. Gives me an extra pawn and I'm back in the game.}
37... Rxf3 38. Kg2 Rb3 {Position is equal according to engine, but of course we
can only try our best. White has to push his kingside pawns, while Black uses
the slight material advantage to impede and create chances of its own.} 39. Be1
Nf6 40. Nc4 Nd5 41. Ne5+ Kg7 42. h4 Ne3+ {All checks just look tempting.} 43.
Kf2 Nc2 {Attacks a piece and a pawn.} 44. Nf3 {White tries to hold on to both.}
44... Rxf3+ {I sac my rook for both pieces. My thinking is that I can use my
knight to jump around and pick up all those pawns. I thought this was the best I
could do, play for a draw.} (44... Nxe1 {Actually it's better to keep the rook
against knight and use the material to force a win. This would've been hard for
me to see.} 45. Nxe1 Ra3 46. Ke2 Rxa4 47. Nc2 Ra2 48. Kd3 Rxc2) 45. Kxf3 Nxe1+
46. Kf4 Kf6 47. g5+ Kg6 {I fear this is a step in the wrong direction, as it
allows the white king to invade.} 48. Ke5 Nf3+ 49. Kd6 Nxd4 {I grab my first
pawn. I see the draw now. The knight will grab every last one, but Black will
lose all its pawns too.} 50. Kc7 Nb3 {Routine now. We both just need to play
through the motions.} 51. a5 {A blunder. Guus sees it as soon as his hand leaves
the pawn, and he smacks his head. The knight now protects the pawn and Black can
win this game. Or so I think.} (51. Kxb7 {All White had to do.} 51... Nxc5+ 52.
Kb6 Nxa4+ 53. Kxa6 Nb2 54. Kb6) (51. Kb6 a5) 51... Nxc5 52. Kb6 {White plays
this thinking he has lost.} 52... Nb3 {But this is one last blunder.} (52...
Nd7+ {This actually does win.} 53. Kxb7 c5 54. Kxa6 c4 55. Kb5 c3 56. a6 c2 57.
a7 c1=Q 58. a8=Q Qc5+ 59. Ka4 (59. Ka6)) 53. Kxb7 c5 {White resigns the game
here ! But in fact the game is drawn. Black can either race the pawn to
promotion OR sac the knight for white's pawn, but I can't do both ! So white
will be getting a queen too !} 54. Kc7 (54. Kxa6 c4 (54... Nxa5 {Saccing too
early actually loses the game.} 55. Kxa5 c4 56. Kb4) 55. Kb5 {Black must now
pick a poison.} 55... c3 (55... Nxa5 56. Kb4 c3 57. Kxc3 {Black will reach the
h4 pawn before White's king can get there.} 57... Nc6) 56. a6 c2 57. a7 c1=Q 58.
a8=Q Qc5+ 59. Ka4 Qc4+ 60. Ka3 Qxh4) 0-1

