1. f4 {Rapid tournament in Amsterdam West. I missed the first 4 rounds held
earlier, but so did many others.} 1... e6 {I've played Q before once, in a
classical game. She struck me as a bit of a newbie (she eventually flagged), and
I feel this should be an easy game for me.} 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Bd7 4. d4 c5 5. c3
Qb6 6. Bd3 c4 7. Bc2 Ne7 8. O-O f6 9. Nbd2 Ng6 10. e4 Nxf4 {I didn't see that I
was losing a pawn this way, just playing too fast. White is apparently better
though.} 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Be4 {I touched my bishop and didn't move it, because
I saw the knight fork. I let go of it and kept thinking for another minute. Q
eventually reminded me of touch move. I smiled and agreed.} 12... Ne3 13. Qe2
Nxf1 14. Qxf1 e5 15. Qxc4 Bb5 {Hurrah I'm back.} 16. Qc8+ Qd8 17. Qxd8+ (17.
Qxb7 {Was better.} 17... a6) 17... Kxd8 18. Bxb7 Bc6 19. Bxa8 Bxa8 20. dxe5 Bc5+
21. Kf1 fxe5 22. Nxe5 Rf8+ 23. Nef3 (23. Ndf3) 23... Be4 {Total blunder. Just
didn't see the knight.} 24. Nxe4 {[%c_effect
f1;square;f1;type;Winner;animated;true,d8;square;d8;type;ResignBlack;animated;true]}
1-0

[Event "SGA 3e Klasse A"]
[Site "Amsterdam"]
[Date "2025.03.06"]
[Round "5"]
[White "Harman Singh"]
[Black "Oomen, Samuel"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "1584"]
[BlackElo "1364"]
[TimeControl "5400+15"]

1. f4 {A full grimace from my opponent.} 1... d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {Annoying
but I will ignore.} 4. d4 {Revealing the intent to play Stonewall.} 4... e6 5.
Bd3 c5 6. c3 {Escape square for the bishop.} 6... cxd4 7. exd4 (7. cxd4 {Allows
the knight to come out and maybe dive onto b4.} 7... Nc6) 7... Bd6 {This targets
a pawn defended by a distant bishop. In order to develop the knight to d2, White
must play Ne5 first, for which White must unpin the queen first, for which White
must castle first. The 4 moves are fixed.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe1 Nbd7 10. Ne5 Bxe5??
{[%c_effect e5;square;e5;type;Blunder;persistent;true]} 11. fxe5 Ne8 {With the
departure of this knight, I'm having dreams of Greek gifts. It never happens but
it is always in the air.} 12. Nd2 (12. Qg3 Bh5 13. Qh3 Bg6 14. Bxg6 hxg6) 12...
Qg5 {Sus move, allows discovered double attacks on the queen.} 13. Rf4 {Stupid,
flashy move that doesn't achieve much. I just wanted to feel cool. I nodded at
my opponent who was at the coffee table so he would come back to the table just
to watch me make this epic looking move.} (13. Nf3 Qh5 (13... Qe7 14. Bxh7+
{GIFT} 14... Kxh7 15. Ng5+ Kg8 16. Qh4) 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Rxf3) (13. Ne4 Qe7)
13... f6 (13... Qxf4 {Taking the free rook results in the queen getting
trapped.} 14. Nf3 {Beautiful arrangement with twin bishops.} (14. Nb3)) 14. Nf3
Bxf3 {Mistake. White will now attack the queen repeatedly till the h7 pawn is
won.} 15. Rxf3 Qh5 16. Rh3 Qg4 17. Bxh7+ {Unnecessary really, since the queen is
about to be trapped anyway, but why say no to a free pawn ?} 17... Kf7 18. Rh4
{Resigned.} 1-0

[Event "SGA 4e Klasse"]
[Site "Amsterdam"]
[Date "2025.04.08"]
[Round "7"]
[White "Verheijden, Chris"]
[Black "Harman Singh"]
[Result "0-1"]
[WhiteElo "1643"]
[BlackElo "1552"]
[TimeControl "5400+15"]

1. e4 {I'm playing Board 6 in an away match against Caissa 7. It's the
penultimate round of the season and we're in contention for promotion. Need a
win though.} 1... d6 {My opponent Chris is easily the youngest player in his
team, he looks like he's 20. Everyone is 45+.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be2 Bg7
5. O-O O-O 6. d4 Nbd7 {Unnecessary.} (6... e5 {Already works.} 7. dxe5 dxe5 8.
Nxe5 (8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Nxe5 Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Bxe5)) 7. h3 {Very cautious play.} 7...
e5 8. Be3 exd4 9. Nxd4 Re8 10. Bd3 Ne5 (10... Nc5 {Was maybe better. White must
now defend the e pawn and lose the bishop pair.} 11. Qf3 Nxd3 12. cxd3) 11. Qd2
{A tactic emerges. If the d4 knight is kicked away, Black can play Bxh3.} 11...
c5 12. Ndb5 {Allows another kick.} (12. Nde2 {Was apparently better.} 12... Bxh3
13. Nf4 Be6 14. Nxe6 Rxe6) 12... a6 13. Na3 Bxh3 {Got excited about this move
and played it too quick, but there were better options.} (13... b5 {This is a
scarier move as it threatens to win a piece on the next move so White has to
respond immediately. The h3 pawn can be won later.} 14. Nd1 c4 {Another tempo
move. Black is in no hurry to get that pawn.} 15. Be2 Nxe4 {Black wins a
different pawn entirely. I'm actually happier with the way my game went.}) 14.
f4 (14. gxh3 {White cannot take because it allows a royal fork.} 14... Nf3+)
14... Nxd3 {Trade to save the bishop.} 15. cxd3 Bg4 16. Rae1 b5 {Finally
threatening to win a piece.} 17. Nd1 c4 {Moving that d3 pawn would allow my
knight to come to e4 with tempo.} (17... Rxe4 {Kamil, the mad man sitting next
to me on Board 6, recommends sacrificing a rook for 2 pawns here. Says Black's
pieces are well places and White's aren't. I could never play like this. Too
brave for me.} 18. dxe4 Nxe4) 18. Nf2 cxd3 {I'm okay with Nxg4 because then I
play Nxg4 and my queen arrives at h4.} 19. Qxd3 (19. Nxg4 Nxg4) 19... Rc8 {Never
say no to an open file.} 20. Bd4 Be6 {Dreams of playing b4 and then skewering
the queen and rook from c4. This never happens.} 21. b3 d5 22. exd5 Qxd5 {Nice,
active queen.} (22... Bxd5 {Would've been a terrible mistake.} 23. Bxf6 Bxf6 24.
Rxe8+ Qxe8 25. Qxd5) 23. Re5 {Bold, fancy move, but I can threaten back with a
cheaper piece.} 23... Bf5 {Overall this works out for me, but because of reasons
I didn't fully calculate.} 24. Rxd5 {A bad queen trade, but not for the reasons
I expected.} (24. Qe3 {I was expecting the White queen to just move.}) 24...
Bxd3 {I thought attacking two rooks meant I would win one and be up an
exchange.} 25. Bxf6 {But White has this nice intermezzo with a discovered attack
on the d3 bishop. Now I (seemingly) have to take a rook for 2 pieces.} 25...
Bxf1 26. Bxg7 {White thinks he's alright, but...} 26... Re1 {Another intermezzo
! Threatens a discovered check could win a rook.} (26... Rc1 {Saw this move
first but fortunately picked the correct rook to move.}) 27. Re5 {A clever
defense from White. Trading rooks now would keep material even again.} (27. Be5
{Demo of the discovered check.} 27... Bc4+ 28. Kh2 Bxd5) (27. Rd1 {This was the
best defense that White had to find.} 27... Rxd1 (27... Rc1 {This was planned
response and boy am I glad I didn't play it. White traps a rook and secures
perpetual.} 28. Rxc1 Rxc1 29. Bb2 Re1 30. Bc3 Rc1 31. Bb2 Re1) 28. Nxd1
{Materially even again, and 2 knights are always scary.} 28... Kxg7 29. Kxf1)
27... Be2+ {My best find of the game. Discovered check while shielding the
rook.} 28. Kh2 Kxg7 {Black is now up an exchange and a pawn. This game is
getting easier.} 29. Nd3 Rd1 30. Nc5 Rd2 31. Nb1 (31. Nxa6 Rxa2 32. Nb4 Rxa3 33.
Rxe2 Rxb3) 31... Rxa2 {Played this knowing full well there's a fork.} (31... Rb2
{Another option, but without winning the a pawn.} 32. Nc3 Bf1 33. Kg1 Bxg2) 32.
Nxa6 (32. Nc3 Rc2 33. Nxe2 R8xc5 {Happy with this.}) 32... Rxa6 {Played this
thinking I've trapped the knight too.} 33. Rxe2 Ra1 {Knight cannot be defended
!} 34. Rb2 {Uuhhh yes it can.} (34. Nd2 Rc2) 34... Rc1 35. Nd2 Re1 {Threatens to
pin.} 36. Nf3 Rab1 {Ignore the threat and invite a trade. All I want to do is
pick up that b pawn.} 37. Rd2 Red1 38. Kg3 {White seemingly gives up and allows
the rook trade. This allow relinquishes the b pawn.} 38... Rxd2 39. Nxd2 Rb2
{Kick.} 40. Ne4 Rxb3+ {And now there's a clear plan to victory. Use the rook to
walk the b pawn up the board. White will need to sac the knight to stay in the
game.} 41. Kg4 b4 42. Nc5 Re3 43. g3 b3 44. Na4 Re2 45. Nc3 Rh2 (45... b2
{Considered giving up my rook and getting a queen, but rook vs nothing seemed
easier than queen vs knight.}) 46. Kf3 {White just having fun now.} 46... b2 47.
Ke3 Rh1 {White resigns. Poor fellow seemed distraught, but I think we both
played well enough. Very tactical game and that middlegame queen trade was
pretty intense.} (47... Rc2 48. Kd3 Rxc3+ 49. Kxc3 b1=Q) 0-1

