1. d4 {Nemo is visiting Amsterdam and we are playing on a fabric board in the
Bentinckstraat living room. There is a chess clock beside the board but we're
only using it to keep track of whose turn it is.} 1... g6 2. Bf4 d6 3. e3 Nf6 4.
Nf3 Bg7 5. Bc4 a6 6. O-O O-O 7. c3 Nc6 8. Qb3 e6 9. Nbd2 b5 10. Bd3 Re8 11. c4
Na5 12. Qc3 c6 13. cxb5 axb5 14. b4 e5 15. bxa5 exf4 16. e4 c5 17. Bxb5 cxd4 18.
Nxd4 Bd7 19. Rab1 Bxb5 20. Rxb5 Qe7 21. Re1 Rac8 22. Qf3 d5 23. e5 Ne4 24. Nxe4
dxe4 25. Rxe4 {White blunders backrank mate in 3. It's easy to spot, but Black
decides to complicate things for no reason. When you find mate, look for
better.} 25... Qxe5 {Completely unnecessary queen sac. White can take in 2
different ways but both lead to mate.} (25... Rc1+ 26. Qd1 Rxd1+ 27. Re1 Rxe1#)
26. h3 {What Black fails to consider is that White can simply decline the stupid
queen sac. Game goes on.} (26. Rexe5 Rc1+ 27. Qd1 Rxd1+ 28. Re1 Rexe1#) (26.
Rbxe5 Rc1+ 27. Qd1 Rxd1+ 28. Re1 Rxe1+ 29. Rxe1 Rxe1#) 26... Qxe4 {A pure stroke
of luck for Black that there is a rook to be won here.} 27. Qxe4 {Unnecessary
queen trade.} 27... Rxe4 28. Nf3 Ra4 29. g4 fxg3 30. fxg3 Rxa2 31. Ne1 Bc3 32.
Kf1 Bxe1 {[%c_effect g8;square;g8;type;Winner;animated;true]} 0-1

