30. Qe1 Bxg2 31. Kxg2 Qd5+ 32. Kg1 Rf8?? {[%c_effect
f8;square;f8;type;Blunder;size;100%25;animated;false;persistent;true] Big
blunder, but I'm still figuring out what the winning plan was. My thinking was
to trade pieces and strengthen my protected passed, but the engine says it's
drawish now.} (32... b5 33. Na3 (33. Nb2 e2 34. Rf2 Re3) 33... Qd6 34. Nb1 e2
35. Rf2 Nxb1) (32... Qe6) (32... Qh5 33. Kg2 (33. a5) (33. h3) (33. b4 Ne2+ 34.
Kg2 Qd5+ 35. Kh3 Nc3)) 33. Nxe3! {[%c_effect
e3;square;e3;type;GreatFind;size;100%25;animated;false;persistent;true]} 33...
Rxf1+ {A good find.} (33... dxe3? {[%c_effect
e3;square;e3;type;Mistake;size;100%25;animated;false;persistent;true]}) 34. Nxf1
{Any other recapture would lose a piece.} (34. Kxf1 Qf3+ 35. Kg1 (35. Qf2 Qh1+
36. Qg1 Qf3+ 37. Qf2) 35... Qh1+ (35... Qxe3+) (35... Ne2+ 36. Qxe2 Qxe2)) (34.
Qxf1 dxe3) 34... Qf3 {Unnecessarily flashy. I'm setting up a simple mate with
Ne2#, but I'm also clearly allowing a perpetual.} 35. Qe7+ {Robbert immediately
offers a draw, and I can see it's legit. But we're both under 1 min now and it's
about to be a supremely complicated knight-v-knight endgame. I don't trust my
calculation skills but I trust my nerves under time pressure. I decline.} 35...
Qf7 36. Qe5+ Kg8 37. Nd2 Qg7 38. Nf3 c5 39. Qe6+ (39. Qe8+ Kh7 40. Qe6 Nd1)
