1. e4 {I'm playing Board 6 in an away match against Caissa 7. It's the
penultimate round of the season and we're in contention for promotion. Need a
win though.} 1... d6 {My opponent Chris is easily the youngest player in his
team, he looks like he's 20. Everyone is 45+.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be2 Bg7
5. O-O O-O 6. d4 Nbd7 {Unnecessary.} (6... e5 {Already works.} 7. dxe5 dxe5 8.
Nxe5 (8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Nxe5 Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Bxe5)) 7. h3 {Very cautious play.} 7...
e5 8. Be3 exd4 9. Nxd4 Re8 10. Bd3 Ne5 (10... Nc5 {Was maybe better. White must
now defend the e pawn and lose the bishop pair.} 11. Qf3 Nxd3 12. cxd3) 11. Qd2
{A tactic emerges. If the d4 knight is kicked away, Black can play Bxh3.} 11...
c5 12. Ndb5? {[%c_effect
b5;square;b5;type;Mistake;size;100%25;animated;false;persistent;true] Allows
another kick.} (12. Nde2 {Was apparently better.} 12... Bxh3 13. Nf4 Be6 14.
Nxe6 Rxe6) 12... a6 13. Na3 Bxh3? {[%c_effect
h3;square;h3;type;Mistake;size;100%25;animated;false;persistent;true] Got
excited about this move and played it too quick, but there were better options.}
(13... b5 {This is a scarier move as it threatens to win a piece on the next
move so White has to respond immediately. The h3 pawn can be won later.} 14. Nd1
c4 {Another tempo move. Black is in no hurry to get that pawn.} 15. Be2 Nxe4
{Black wins a different pawn entirely. I'm actually happier with the way my game
went.}) 14. f4?! {[%c_effect
f4;square;f4;type;Inaccuracy;size;100%25;animated;false;persistent;true]} (14.
gxh3 {White cannot take because it allows a royal fork.} 14... Nf3+) 14... Nxd3
{Trade to save the bishop.} 15. cxd3 Bg4 16. Rae1 b5 {Finally threatening to win
a piece.} 17. Nd1 c4 {Moving that d3 pawn would allow my knight to come to e4
with tempo.} (17... Rxe4 {Kamil, the mad man sitting next to me on Board 6,
recommends sacrificing a rook for 2 pawns here. Says Black's pieces are well
places and White's aren't. I could never play like this. Too brave for me.} 18.
dxe4 Nxe4) 18. Nf2 cxd3 {I'm okay with Nxg4 because then I play Nxg4 and my
queen arrives at h4.} 19. Qxd3 (19. Nxg4 Nxg4) 19... Rc8 {Never say no to an
open file.} 20. Bd4 Be6 {Dreams of playing b4 and then skewering the queen and
rook from c4. This never happens.} 21. b3 d5 22. exd5 Qxd5 {Nice, active queen.}
(22... Bxd5 {Would've been a terrible mistake.} 23. Bxf6 Bxf6 24. Rxe8+ Qxe8 25.
Qxd5) 23. Re5 {Bold, fancy move, but I can threaten back with a cheaper piece.}
23... Bf5?! {[%c_effect
f5;square;f5;type;Inaccuracy;size;100%25;animated;false;persistent;true] Overall
this works out for me, but because of reasons I didn't fully calculate.} 24.
Rxd5 {A bad queen trade, but not for the reasons I expected.} (24. Qe3 {I was
expecting the White queen to just move.}) 24... Bxd3 {I thought attacking two
rooks meant I would win one and be up an exchange.} 25. Bxf6 {But White has this
nice intermezzo with a discovered attack on the d3 bishop. Now I (seemingly)
have to take a rook for 2 pieces.} 25... Bxf1 26. Bxg7 {White thinks he's
alright, but...} 26... Re1 {Another intermezzo ! Threatens a discovered check
could win a rook.} (26... Rc1 {Saw this move first but fortunately picked the
correct rook to move.}) 27. Re5 {A clever defense from White. Trading rooks now
would keep material even again.} (27. Be5 {Demo of the discovered check.} 27...
Bc4+ 28. Kh2 Bxd5) (27. Rd1 {This was the best defense that White had to find.}
27... Rxd1 (27... Rc1 {This was planned response and boy am I glad I didn't play
it. White traps a rook and secures perpetual.} 28. Rxc1 Rxc1 29. Bb2 Re1 30. Bc3
Rc1 31. Bb2 Re1) 28. Nxd1 {Materially even again, and 2 knights are always
scary.} 28... Kxg7 29. Kxf1) 27... Be2+! {[%c_effect
e2;square;e2;type;GreatFind;size;100%25;animated;false;persistent;true] My best
find of the game. Discovered check while shielding the rook.} 28. Kh2 Kxg7!
{[%c_effect
g7;square;g7;type;GreatFind;size;100%25;animated;false;persistent;true] Black is
now up an exchange and a pawn. This game is getting easier.} 29. Nd3 Rd1 30. Nc5
Rd2 31. Nb1 (31. Nxa6 Rxa2 32. Nb4 Rxa3 33. Rxe2 Rxb3) 31... Rxa2 {Played this
knowing full well there's a fork.} (31... Rb2 {Another option, but without
winning the a pawn.} 32. Nc3 Bf1 33. Kg1 Bxg2) 32. Nxa6 (32. Nc3 Rc2 33. Nxe2
R8xc5 {Happy with this.}) 32... Rxa6 {Played this thinking I've trapped the
knight too.} 33. Rxe2 Ra1 {Knight cannot be defended !} 34. Rb2 {Uuhhh yes it
can.} (34. Nd2 Rc2) 34... Rc1 35. Nd2 Re1 {Threatens to pin.} 36. Nf3 Rab1
{Ignore the threat and invite a trade. All I want to do is pick up that b pawn.}
37. Rd2 Red1 38. Kg3 {White seemingly gives up and allows the rook trade. This
allow relinquishes the b pawn.} 38... Rxd2 39. Nxd2 Rb2 {Kick.} 40. Ne4 Rxb3+
{And now there's a clear plan to victory. Use the rook to walk the b pawn up the
board. White will need to sac the knight to stay in the game.} 41. Kg4 b4 42.
Nc5 Re3 43. g3 b3 44. Na4 Re2 45. Nc3 Rh2 (45... b2 {Considered giving up my
rook and getting a queen, but rook vs nothing seemed easier than queen vs
knight.}) 46. Kf3 {White just having fun now.} 46... b2 47. Ke3 Rh1 {[%c_effect
g7;square;g7;type;Winner;animated;true] White resigns. Poor fellow seemed
distraught, but I think we both played well enough. Very tactical game and that
middlegame queen trade was pretty intense.} (47... Rc2 48. Kd3 Rxc3+ 49. Kxc3
b1=Q) 0-1

