1. f4 {Satisfying grimace from my opponent.} 1... d5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. d4
{Sneak stonewall.} 4... Nf6 5. Bd3 O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 7. c3 {Escape square for
bishop.} 7... cxd4 (7... c4 8. Bc2) 8. exd4 (8. cxd4) 8... Nbd7 9. O-O Qb6 {Pins
the d pawn and annoys me for the rest of the game.} 10. Qe1 (10. Kh1 {Considered
this just to avoid problems.}) (10. Qb3 {Considered this as a developing move,
cos Black wouldn't want to trade.} 10... Qxb3 11. axb3) 10... Re8 11. Ne5 Nxe5
12. fxe5 Nd7 {Targets the vulnerable e pawn.} 13. Qf2 {Interesting move, unpins
the d pawn and also target Black's f pawn.} (13. a3 {If White plays a nothing
move here Black can grab the e pawn.} 13... Bxe5 (13... Nxe5 {This variant
doesn't work because of the mate threat.} 14. Qf2 Nd7 15. Qxf7+) 14. Qf2 Bf6)
13... f6 14. exf6 Bxf6 {Strange, I would've captured with the knight to unblock
the dormant bishop.} 15. Nf3 {Unblocks the dormant bishop.} 15... Rf8 {Love to
see this, my bishop is headed for h6.} 16. Bh6 Bg7 (16... Rf7 {I was hoping to
see this but of course it would be terrible for Black.}) 17. Qh4 {I'm liking the
attacking potential here.} (17. Bxg7 {Trading immediately also works, as seen in
this engine line.} 17... Kxg7 18. Qe3 Re8 19. Ne5 a6 20. Rf7+ Kg8) 17... e5
{Poor move IMO, allows the knight to join in. I think the idea was save this
pawn from a queen fork on e7 and also to pressure White's still-pinned d pawn.}
18. Bxg7 {Very bad miss. Bringing the knight in early is much much better.} (18.
Ng5 {Now everything is good.} 18... a6 (18... Bxh6 19. Qxh6 Nf6 20. Rxf6 Rxf6
21. Qxh7+ Kf8 22. Qh8+ Ke7) 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Qxh7#) 18... Kxg7 {Now Ng5 isn't
as scary since it can be kicked by the h pawn.} 19. Ng5 (19. Nxe5 {Engine says
sac the knight $1 Look what happens if Black takes.} 19... Nxe5 20. Rxf8 Kxf8
21. Rf1+ Kg8 22. Qf4 Nd7 (22... Nf7) 23. Qf7+ Kh8 24. Qe8+ Kg7 25. Rf7+ Kh6 26.
Qe3+ Kh5 27. Be2+ Kh4 28. Rxh7#) 19... h6 {Shoo.} 20. Rf7+ {Deranged sacrifice
of a full knight. I was to bring the king onto the f file, then check with the
a-rook, then bring my queen in and hope for a mate to just appear. I wish I
wouldn't play stuff like this without at least trying to calculate the lines. I
do think that there is a potential perpetual here once my queen comes in, but
even that's mostly a dream. Surprisingly the engine doesn't completely hate the
move, making this one of my first ever fully intuitive positional sacrifices.}
(20. Ne4 {Engine says sac the knight a different way. Black shouldn't take.}
20... dxe4 21. Qe7+ Kh8 22. Rxf8+ Nxf8 23. Qxf8+ Kh7 24. Qf7+ Kh8) 20... Rxf7
21. Nxf7 Kxf7 (21... exd4 {Jonathan tells me he considers just ignoring the
knight and plays something else, confident that his king would be able to
escape. He's wrong though.} 22. Rf1 (22. Qxh6+) 22... dxc3+ 23. Kh1 Nf6 24.
Qxh6+ Kxf7 25. Qxg6+ Ke7 26. Qg7+ Kd6 27. Rxf6+) 22. Rf1+ {This very intuitive
move is actually a miss and allows Black sufficient defense.} (22. Qxh6 Ke7 23.
Rf1 Kd8 24. Qg5+ Kc7 25. Bxg6) 22... Nf6 (22... Kg7 23. Qe7+ Kh8 24. Qe8+)
(22... Ke8 23. Qxh6) 23. Qxh6 Bf5 {Completely missed this move. I need to trade
to keep my rook pin alive, which means my bishop won't be a part of this attack.
Sacrifice looking worse and worse.} 24. Bxf5 gxf5 25. Rxf5 Rg8 {During the game
I thought this was a fairly clever move, blocking the incoming queen checks. But
the engine dislikes.} (25... a6 26. Rxf6+ (26. Qh7+ Kf8 27. Qh8+ Kf7 28. Qh7+
Kf8 29. Qg6 exd4 30. Rxf6+ Qxf6 31. Qxf6+) 26... Qxf6 27. Qxf6+ Kxf6) (25...
exd4 26. Qh7+ Ke6 27. Qg6 d3+ 28. Kh1 Rf8) 26. Qh7+ Rg7 27. Qh5+ {My knight sac
hasn't worked out so I'd be very happy with a draw by repetition now. Black
needs to find Kg8 to avoid it. He's low on time, and I'm ready to play Qf3
whenever he does find it.} 27... Rg6 28. Qh7+ Rg7 {Giving me hope.} 29. Qh5+ Kg8
{Black finds the move.} 30. Qf3 {Engine dislikes, but I like my chances now. My
moves have been simple and uncomplicated, and I'm playing quick. Jonathan needs
to avoid losing material and it's harder for him with low time.} (30. Qh6 Qxb2
31. g3 Qb1+ 32. Rf1 Rg6) 30... Rf7 31. Qg3+ {I'm playing my moves a bit
erratically and I think this unsettles him a bit, not being able to mirror my
pace. This moves picks up the e5 pawn and after that I'm feeling a lot safer.}
31... Rg7 32. Qxe5 {No more pin dangers. Black is playing with 5-7 seconds on
the clock now.} 32... Ne4 {He places his knight on an attractive outpost, but
it's a blunder that lets me pick up a pawn, fork the knight, and finally make
good on that knight sac way back when.} 33. Qxd5+ {Now I'm winning, with 4 extra
pawns.} 33... Kh7 {But it doesn't matter. Black flags before he can play this
move. He spends a few minutes in analysis explaining to me that he was easily
winning this game but only lost due to time. He disregards that his last legal
move ensured that he wasn't winning on the board either.} 1-0

