1. d4 {Internal competition game with Tom, and my first game against him. He's
won 3 wins in 3 games so far, but they're against relatively newer players. So I
don't know anything at all about his level.} 1... g6 {Modern defense to avoid
the Tromposwsky, with plans to transpose to Pirc later.} 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. e4 d6 4.
Bf4 {Indicating that he might be aware of the 150 attack.} 4... c6 {Anti 150
attack.} 5. Nf3 {Indicating that he is not aware of the 150 attack.} 5... Nbd7
6. Be2 Bg7 7. Qd2 {Indicating that he might still use some ideas from the 150
attack.} 7... b5 {Back to my anti 150.} 8. Rb1 {Very strange move. He said later
that he didn't know why he played it either. I guess this means I can safely
castle kingside.} 8... b4 {Kicks the knight and we will pick up a pawn each.} 9.
Nd1 (9. Na4) 9... Nxe4 10. Qxb4 O-O 11. Ne3 Qb6 {Offers an early queen trade to
fix my h pawn and activate my rook.} 12. Qxb6 axb6 13. a3 Bb7 14. Ng5 {Tom
appeared to immediately regret playing this move so I thought for a while here
trying to find what he didn't like, but found nothing.} 14... Nxg5 (14... e5 15.
Nxe4 (15. dxe5 dxe5) 15... exf4 16. Nxd6 fxe3 17. Nxb7) 15. Bxg5 {More pawns
being exchanged, but my rook is about to get an open file to his king, which I
like.} 15... Bxd4 16. Bxe7 Rfe8 17. Bxd6 Bxe3 18. fxe3 Rxe3 19. Kf2 Rae8 20. Bg4
Nf6 21. Bf3 R3e6 22. Bg3 Ne4+ {Further simplifying, because I'm now a bit low on
time.} 23. Bxe4 Rxe4 24. Rbe1 Kg7 {I considered trading into an endgame but
didn't like my king placement.} (24... Rxe1 25. Rxe1 Rxe1 26. Kxe1 c5 27. Kf2
(27. c4 Bxg2)) 25. Rxe4 Rxe4 {From this point on I'm playing with under 4
minutes while Tom has about 9. I didn't pay attention to this during the game
but he starts to make several 'random' moves, indicating that he was
uncomfortable with the time too, or maybe he was just trying to unsettle me. It
definitely worked.} 26. Rd1 Re7 27. b4 {This is definitely an 'unthinking'
move.} 27... Ba6 {Trying to play Re2 and pick up a pawn.} 28. Rd2 f5 {Ideas of
trapping a bishop.} 29. Kf3 Kf6 30. Bf2 b5 (30... c5 {Engine says this is fine,
but I'm down a pawn so engine please keep quiet.} 31. bxc5 bxc5 32. Bxc5 Rc7 33.
Bd4+ Kg5 34. c3) 31. g4 {Hurried again, and I could've probably taken.} 31...
Bc8 (31... fxg4+ 32. Kxg4 Bc8+ 33. Kg3) 32. h3 fxg4+ 33. hxg4 Kg5 34. Be3+ Rxe3+
$4 {Deranged exchange sacrifice. I play it thinking my bishop can pick up the g4
pawn and then come back to defend c6. Now my passed pawns will march.} (34...
Kh4 $4 {My first instinct move would've resulted in mate-in-1.}) 35. Kxe3 Bxg4
36. Rd6 {It's at this point that I realize my calculation doesn't work. The
bishop has no safe way of routing back to defend c6. I'm now down an exchange
for nothing.} 36... Bh3 37. Rxc6 Bf1 38. Kd4 h5 39. Ke3 h4 40. Kf2 Bh3 41. Rc5+
Kf4 42. Rxb5 g5 43. Rd5 g4 {Moves 43-48 are incorrect. We had both stopped
writing by then. By the summary is that Tom missed a crucial bishop check and
the ensuring tempo allowed my pawns to reach the sixth rank.} 44. Kg1 g3 45. Rd6
Bg4 46. b5 Bf5 47. b6 Bc8 48. Kh1 Bb7+ {This move saves the game. The h-pawn
will now promote unless White sacs his rook.} 49. Kg1 h3 50. Rd2 {Tom plays move
with the understanding that he's kind of thrown the game. I have about 45
seconds left on my clock but I take my time to check whether there's a way to
win this. I see nothing, and I'm just relieved that a draw is possible.} 50...
h2+ (50... g2 $4) 51. Rxh2 gxh2+ 52. Kxh2 Ke3 {Black king can now easily pick up
all the white pawns while the bishop blocks promotion. I offer a draw and Tom
accepts.} 1/2-1/2

