1. e4 d6 {SGA match against Sv Amsterdam West. My opponent, Q, came in a bit
late. I started her clock about a minute in, when she had already arrived and
we'd shaken hands.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. b3 {This is a common blunder against the Pirc,
opening tunnel vision so you don't see your e4 pawn is threatened. But Q told me
later that this was intentional, she's giving up a pawn \"to open lines.\" I
don't know how much weight to put in this, since she's clearly new to the game
but giving up this pawn did give her a big lead in development later.} 3... Nxe4
4. Bd3 Nf6 (4... d5 {Could be played to avoid losing tempo, but I preferred a
pawn structure I was familiar with.}) 5. Bb2 e5 (5... Nbd7) 6. Nc3 g6 7. O-O
{White is castled and fully developed. Black is a pawn up but that's all.} 7...
Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. Qe2 {Weak move IMO. The queen should be behind the rook, not
in front.} 9... Nc6 10. Bb5 Nd4 {Played this cos I'm envisioning a line in which
I win a piece, but it devolves into hope chess and I abandoned the plan later.}
11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Ne4 Nxe4 {Inaccuracy according to the engine, likely because
it makes the queen active and double attacks the d4 pawn.} (12... Ng4 {Engine
recommendation. I didn't even consider it.}) (12... d3?? {[%c_effect
d3;square;d3;type;Blunder;persistent;true] Glad I didn't play this but I spent a
lot of time thinking about it.} 13. Qxd3 Nxe4?? {[%c_effect
e4;square;e4;type;Blunder;persistent;true]} 14. Bxg7 Nc5) 13. Qxe4 c6 {Many bad
moves for the bishop, hoping she makes one of them.} 14. Bd3 Bf5 {Thinking that
after the queen moves I can double White's pawns on the d file, but this isn't
forced.} 15. Qf3 {Now the queen can recapture the bishop if needed.} 15... Be6
{I don't want to trade bishops and queen, especially cos it'll give me doubled
pawns on the f file.} (15... Qd7 16. Bxf5 Qxf5 17. Qxf5 gxf5) 16. c4 dxc3
{Played this move when my opponent was away from the table, and she had a big
frown on her face when she got back. Think she had forgotten this was possible.}
17. dxc3 {Obvious move to avoid an isolated queen pawn, but engine likes Bxc3
better, possibly because it eliminates my strong bishop.} (17. Bxc3 Qg5 18. Bxg7
Kxg7) 17... Bd5 {Just tempo tricks.} 18. Be4 Bxe4 19. Rxe4 {Weirdly I hadn't
expected this. Thought she'd retake with the queen.} 19... d5 20. Re2 Qd7 {Can't
move far because White is about to double their rooks and we will need to
contest.} 21. Rae1 Rae8 {Contesting the open file, planning to trade away the
rooks since I'm still up a pawn.} 22. Ba3 {Strange move I thought. Allows trades
to happen and the bishop just seems out of place there. Later this will allow me
to pick up the c3 pawn.} 22... Rxe2 23. Rxe2 (23. Qxe2 {Loses another pawn and
prompts trades.} 23... Bxc3 24. Bxf8 Bxe1 25. Bh6 (25. Qxe1 Kxf8)) 23... Re8
{Still planning to trade away and win the c3 pawn.} 24. h3 {Mistake, drops a
pawn.} 24... Rxe2 25. Qxe2 Bxc3 26. Qe3 d4 {Strong outpost now.} 27. Qh6
{Threatening checkmate on f8. Suddenly the a3 bishop looks great.} 27... Qe8 28.
Bc1 {Mistake IMO. Bishop was great on a3. But Q is under time pressure now,
she's down to about 5 minutes vs 50 minutes for me.} 28... Qe1+ 29. Kh2 d3 {Took
some time here and played this with great confidence. I thought this pawn was
unstoppable now.} 30. Ba3 {Threatening mate again.} 30... Be5+?! {[%c_effect
e5;square;e5;type;Inaccuracy;persistent;true] Unnecessary complication. Did not
even anticipate f4. I was thinking g3, following by some mating attack.} 31. f4
(31. g3 Qxf2+ 32. Kh1 Qf3+ 33. Kg1 Bd4+ 34. Kh2 Qf2+ 35. Kh1 Qg1#) 31... Bg7 32.
Qg5 {The mate on f8 threat seems more real now.} 32... h6?! {[%c_effect
h6;square;h6;type;Inaccuracy;persistent;true] I thought I was just giving my
king an escape square, but in reality this loses my precious d3 passed pawn. f6
and Qe8 were both better options.} (32... d2?? {[%c_effect
d2;square;d2;type;Blunder;persistent;true] A casual move from Black here
would've ended the game.} 33. Qd8+ Bf8 34. Qxf8#) 33. Qd8+ Kh7 34. Qxd3
{Mentally this is my low point in the game. I'd been winning all this time and
now, when Q is playing with under 2 minutes on the clock, I'm blundering away
passed pawns. Because of the extra pawn and the time pressure I'm still likely
to win, but I'm still pretty annoyed with myself for taking so long.} 34... Qf2
35. Bd6 Bd4 36. Qc4 {There's a fairly simple mating attack here, but I'm worried
that if I get something wrong, White has draw by perpetual with Qxf7.} 36... Kg7
{[%c_effect g7;square;g7;type;Winner;animated;true] So no risks. Going to play
slow and win anyway. At this point my opponent thought for a full two minutes
and flagged. It's unfortunate but this happens a lot to new players, they simply
forget to look at the clock.} (36... Qg1+ {Here's what the mating attack
would've looked like.} 37. Kg3 Qe1+ 38. Kf3 (38. Kg4 h5+ 39. Kg5 (39. Kf3 Qe3#)
39... Qg3#) (38. Kh2 Bg1+ 39. Kh1 Bf2+ 40. Kh2 (40. Qf1 Qxf1+ 41. Kh2 Qg1#))
38... Qf2+ 39. Ke4 (39. Kg4 f5#) 39... Qe3#) (36... Qe3 {Here's what the
