1. d4 g6 {My games against Marjolein are destined to be interesting, at least
when she's playing White, because she plays the London system and I play
Pirc-as-a-system. This means for the first 7-8 moves we're each just doing our
own thing, largely ignoring our opponent's setup. There's a lot of potential for
preparation, and I'm coming into this game quite booked up.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4
Bg7 4. Nbd2 d6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. h3 Re8 (7... e5 8. Bh2) 8. O-O e5 {In
hindsight this is maybe a little early, Black could've fianchettoed another
bishop before playing e5. Also if the objective was to play e4-c5 to kick the
knight multiple times, then a6 should be played first to rob the knight of the
b5 outpost.} (8... a6 9. Bh2 e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Be2 e4 12. Nd4 c5 13. N4b3) 9.
dxe5 dxe5 10. Bg5! {[%c_effect
g5;square;g5;type;GreatFind;keyPressed;undefined;persistent;true] This is the
correct response. Bg3 or Bh2 loses a piece to e4.} 10... h6 11. Bxf6 (11. Bh4 g5
{White must sac and will probably still lose.}) 11... Nxf6 12. e4 b6 {It's late
but I still want to fianchetto.} 13. Re1 Bb7 14. Nc4 Nd7 (14... Nh5) 15. Qd2?!
{[%c_effect d2;square;d2;type;Inaccuracy;keyPressed;undefined;persistent;true]}
15... Nc5 {Threatening to secure the bishop pair.} 16. Rad1 a5 17. Nh2
{Amusingly White plays Nh2 like 3 times in this game.} 17... Ba6 {This is a
strange looking move and I think it might be the first 'new' move of the game so
far. I'm eyeing a series of trades that might help my cause.} 18. Ng4 Nxd3 {The
trades begin.} 19. cxd3 (19. Qxd3 Qxd3 {White has to retake with a pawn to avoid
losing the knight.} 20. Rxd3 Bxc4) 19... Bxc4?! {[%c_effect
c4;square;c4;type;Inaccuracy;keyPressed;undefined;persistent;true] I took a long
time to play this move but when I finally did it was with the intention of
getting queens off the board and hopefully one pair of rooks too. I want to play
a bishop-v-knight endgame.} 20. dxc4 Qxd2 21. Rxd2 h5 22. Nh2 {Home.} 22... Rad8
23. Red1?! {[%c_effect
d1;square;d1;type;Inaccuracy;keyPressed;undefined;persistent;true]} 23... Rxd2 ☒
(23... Rd4 {Apparently this is better than a trade and certainly more complex.
If White trades now then I get a passed pawn defended by a bishop and soon
backed by a rook on d8} 24. Rxd4 exd4 25. Nf3 Rxe4 26. Kf1 Re8) 24. Rxd2 Bf6
{Again, just trying to trade rooks.} 25. b3 Rd8 26. Rc2? {[%c_effect
c2;square;c2;type;Mistake;keyPressed;undefined;persistent;true] White finally
refuses a trade. Marjolein says she played this because she wanted to avoid a
draw. I didn't want a draw either, so it's a good thing I now have an open file
for my rook} 26... Rd1+ 27. Nf1 Be7 28. g3 h4? {[%c_effect
h4;square;h4;type;Mistake;keyPressed;undefined;persistent;true] Apparently a
mistake though I can't see why. Engine trades rooks after this and the endgame
is more equal I guess.} 29. g4 ☒ (29. gxh4 Bxh4 30. Kg2 Bg5 31. c5 b5 32. c6 Rc1
33. Rxc1 Bxc1) 29... f6 30. Kg2 Bc5 {Hoping to double White's pawns if the
knight comes to e3.} 31. Nd2 Bb4 32. Nf3 g5 33. Nh2?! {[%c_effect
h2;square;h2;type;Inaccuracy;keyPressed;undefined;persistent;true] Home.} 33...
Kf7 34. Nf1 Bc5 {Again.} 35. Ne3 {This time White allows the trade and allows
doubled pawns. Along with the open file, this makes Black significantly better.}
35... Bxe3 36. fxe3 Re1 {Why then would you give up the open file ??} (36...
Rd3) 37. Rd2 Ke7 {Covering the white rook's invasion squares on d7 and d8.}
(37... Rxe3 {Capturing the pawn instead results in passed pawns for both sides.}
38. Rd7+ Ke6 39. Rxc7 Rxe4 40. Rc6+ Ke7 41. Rxb6) 38. Kf2 Rh1 {Attacking a pawn,
expecting Kg2 and maybe repetition ? Definitely not expecting White to allow a
rook trade.} 39. a3? {[%c_effect
a3;square;a3;type;Mistake;keyPressed;undefined;persistent;true] White allows a
rook trade ! But there's something wrong.} (39. Kg2 Re1) 39... Rxh3 {Calmly take
the pawn instead.} (39... Rh2+ 40. Ke1 {A rook trade now would place the White
king on Kd2, and the Black king has no way to make progress. a3 helps by
blocking an entry square too. This is a dead draw.} 40... Rxd2?? {[%c_effect
d2;square;d2;type;Blunder;keyPressed;undefined;persistent;true]} (40... Rxh3)
41. Kxd2 Kd6 42. Kc3 Kc5) 40. Rd3 Rg3 {The g4 pawn cannot be saved.} 41. Rd1
Rxg4 42. Rg1 {To me this is White just giving up. I'm two pawns ahead, my g- and
h-pawns are unobstructed, so trading rooks is a no-brainer. White should've kept
the rooks to keep fighting.} 42... Rxg1 (42... Rxe4 {Grabbing an extra pawn
seems to complicate things a bit, and who needs it anyway} 43. Kf3 f5 44. Rxg5)
43. Kxg1 Kf7 {All of White's pawns are blocked. Now it's just about advancing g-
and h-pawns. I'm under 1 minute at this point but it's alright cos I could win
this endgame in my sleep.} 44. Kg2 Kg6 45. Kh3 Kh5 46. Kh2 g4 47. Kg2 Kg5 48. a4
f5 49. exf5 Kxf5 50. Kf2 Ke4 51. Ke2 h3 52. Kf2 h2 53. Kg2 Kxe3 54. Kxh2 Kf2 55.
c5 g3+ {[%c_effect f2;square;f2;type;Winner;animated;true]} 0-1

