30. Qf6 Qe6 31. Qxe6 fxe6 32. Rf1 Be7 33. Rf3 Kg7 34. c3 a3 35. b3 bxc3 36. Rxc3
g5 37. Rc7 Kf7 38. b4 {Unbelievably, Black goes on to win this game. White
pushes and manages to successfully queen the b-pawn. Under time pressure, I just
shuffle around, because Kamil is my friend and I know he won't mind me not
resigning. Rather than target and eliminate my bishop, he tries to find a
checkmate and ends up losing his queen to a discovered check. Back to a
rook-v-bishop endgame, I offer a cheeky draw which Kamil refuses with \\\"no
way, not after this\\\". Two moves later he blunders his rook to a bishop fork
and resigns shortly afterwards. I apologized for winning, and he assured me that
I deserved the win for not resigning and continuing to fight. What a gentleman.
I don't know if I'd be capable of a conversation with my opponent after a game
like that.} 38... Kf8 {The next several moves (39-55) aren't legit. We had
stopped writing down our moves cos of the low time on our clocks. I'm just
trying to arrange the pieces as I knew them to be in the end position.} 39. Rc8+
Kg7 40. b5 Kg6 41. b6 g4 42. b7 Kf5 43. b8=Q Bg5 44. Qb1+ Kf4 45. Qb2 Ke3 46.
Qxa3+ Kxd4 47. Qb4+ Kxe5 48. Qe1+ Kd4 49. Qe2 Bc1 50. Rd8 Kc5 51. Kf2 e5 52.
Qxe5 Kc4 53. Ke2 d4 54. Rd7 Bb2 55. Rd6 d3+ 56. Rxd3 Bxe5 57. Rb3 Bxh2 58. Kf2
Bd6 59. Rb6 Bc5+ 60. Kg3 Bxb6 61. Kh4 Bf2+ {[%c_effect
c4;square;c4;type;Winner;animated;true]} 0-1

[Event "SGA 4e Klasse"]
[Site "Amsterdam"]
[Date "2025.02.11"]
[Round "4"]
[White "Roy, Deepayan"]
[Black "Harman Singh"]
[Result "0-1"]
[WhiteElo "1516"]
[BlackElo "1564"]
[TimeControl "5400+15"]

1. d4 g6 {I first met Deepayan at a very casual chess meetup on Pesthuislaan in
early 2023. I was still quite new to serious chess and he destroyed me in a very
quick game. At one point he TRIPLED my pawns (which I did not even realize was a
bad thing at the time) and took a moment to pause, look up at me, and say
\\\"Hmm, tripled pawns, interesting strategy.\\\" In an act of colossal
pettiness, I have disliked him ever since (even though we've car-pooled to
tournaments and played padel together and he's really not that bad). Vishy says
\\\"If revenge motivates you, go for it\\\", so I have looked forward to my
first rated game against him. Sometime in 2024 he visited Zwart op Wit on a
Monday and we played our second casual game. He was winning easily but ended up
blundering a one-move backrank checkmate, which neither of us felt great about.
In January 2025 I was hoping we'd have our first rated game at Wijk aan Zee (our
KNSB ratings were quite similar) but it didn't happen. Finally, in February 2025
Zwart op Wit 3 played an away game against Caissa 6, and Deepayan was the lowest
rated player on their roster. I knew there was a chance of meeting him on Board
8, and that's what happened. Revenge game is on.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 {White is
playing the Colle system.} 3... Bg7 4. Bd3 d6 5. O-O O-O 6. c3 {Looks passive,
but Colle is passive.} 6... Nbd7 7. Nbd2 b6 (7... Re8) 8. e4 e5 9. d5 {I'm happy
with a locked centre, I have had some nice games like this.} 9... a5 {Sheltering
the knight that wants to come to c5.} 10. Re1 Nc5 11. Bc2 a4 {Stops b4 from
kicking the knight. The queenside of the board will now stay dormant for a long
time.} 12. Nf1 Nh5 {Preparing f5.} 13. Bg5 {Happy to see this, f6 comes with
tempo.} 13... f6 14. Bh4 {Bishop should have returned to e3.} 14... g5 {I
thought this was the obvious move. There is no knight sac and I can trade the
bishop off later if I need to. Engine doesn't like it though.} 15. Bg3 f5
{Engine hates this because of the elaborate line starting with exf5.} 16. h3
{Giving the bishop an escape square is an odd move, since Black can always
capture it now.} (16. exf5 Bxf5 17. Bxf5 Rxf5 18. Nxe5 {I did not see this far
ahead.} 18... Nxg3 (18... dxe5 19. Qxh5) 19. Nc6) 16... f4 17. Bh2 g4 18. N3d2
{Lets the queen join the attack.} (18. hxg4 {White had to play this.} 18... Bxg4
19. N1d2) 18... Qg5 19. hxg4 Bxg4 20. Nf3 Qg6 21. N1d2 (21. Nh4 {I initially
thought White could play this and get a repetition because the Black queen has
to return to g5. But the queen trade turns out great for Black, winning two
minor pieces for a rook.} 21... Bxd1 (21... Qg5 22. Nf3 Qg6 23. Nh4 Qg5) 22.
Nxg6 Bxc2 23. Nxf8 Rxf8) 21... Bf6 {Covers the h4 square from the white knight.}
22. b4 {Playing on the wrong side of the board IMO.} 22... Bh3
{\\\"Sacrificing\\\" a knight because I'm threatening mate in one, and because I
think Black's attack will be faster than it really is.} (22... axb3 {I
considered this and there's really no reason NOT to play it, but I just got
excited by my brewing attack.}) 23. Kf1 {I hadn't even thought of Kf1, only the
alternatives g3 and Bg3, both of which looked terrible for White.} (23. g3) (23.
Bg3) 23... Bxg2+ {Big miss, the attack could've fizzled out after this if White
had defended better.} (23... Qxg2+ {Queen taking was much better, but I was
worried about potentially having my queen trapped or pinned with a future Rg1}
24. Ke2 Ng3+ {Did not think of this move while calculating, because I didn't
realize that the f pawn was pinned. Visualisation exercises needed.} 25. Bxg3
fxg3 26. bxc5 Qxf2+ {Maybe it's a good thing that none of this happened because
I would definitely have played this and apparently White is fine after this.}
27. Kd3) 24. Ke2 Nd7 {This sad retreat signals I've run out of attacking ideas
and now just want to hold on to material.} (24... Ng3+ {Knight sac I had no
chance of seeing. The line is too long for me.} 25. fxg3 fxg3 26. Bg1 Qg4 27.
Rf1) 25. Bxa4 {Wins back the pawn and attacks the knight.} (25. Rg1 {This is the
move I was expecting. Black has to move his king first, then work on defending
the pinned bishop.} 25... Kh8 26. Ne1) 25... Bxf3+ {More sad simplification
because I see no attack and I've used up a lot of time.} 26. Nxf3 {Blunders a
pawn and mostly decides the game.} (26. Kxf3 {The move I was expecting.} 26...
Qf7 {Defending the knight.} 27. Rg1+ Kh8) 26... Qxe4+ (26... Rxa4 {Rook sac
works now because taking it would deflect the queen from defending the f3
knight.} 27. Qxa4 Qxe4+ 28. Kd2 Qxf3 29. Qxd7 e4) 27. Kf1 Qc4+ 28. Kg2 b5
{Played this because I thought it wins the pawn on c3.} 29. Nd2 {Attacking the
queen AND the knight on h5, but allowing a check on d5. Many trades will follow,
with Black ending up up a piece, but there was actually a way to defend.} 29...
Qxd5+ 30. Kg1 (30. Ne4 {This lovely move would've defended everything, but White
didn't find it.}) 30... Rxa4 31. Qxh5 (31. Qxa4) 31... Qxd2 32. Qg4+ {Forking
the knight, but White shouldn't take it as it allows rook checks on the king.}
32... Kh8 33. Qxd7 {White takes the hanging knight, but this allows a rook check
on the open g file and checkmate is coming.} 33... Rg8+ 34. Kf1 Bh4 35. Re2 Qxc3
36. Rb1 Qd3 (36... Rxb4 {I'm so bad at finding checkmates that I considered just
playing this, taking another pawn, inviting a rook trade and just winning this
game by attrition.}) 37. Re1 Rxa2 (37... c6 {Considered playing this just to
cheap-trick the white queen away from defending h3 and allowing a pretty
mate-in-one, but I figured if he isn't taking a free pawn on c7, why would he
take it on c6?} 38. Qxd6 Qh3#) 38. Qxc7 {Then he took the free pawn on c7.}
38... Qh3# {[%c_effect
h8;square;h8;type;Winner;animated;true,f1;square;f1;type;CheckmateWhite;animated;true]
Very satisfying.} 0-1

